And when Democrats stand up and they all raise their hand and say we want health insurance paid for by taxpayers, including for abortion for illegal aliens, the question becomes who are they really standing up for? And President Trump has been very good about talking directly to people and saying I'm standing up for Americans, I'm standing up for you. And Democrats seem to be trying to split this conversation about -- well, we're for the American worker, but we're also for all these people who have come here illegally and broken the laws, which is by the way, don't think should be laws anymore.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Maybe they're standing up for American values. Maybe it's the case that the incentive you guys think --

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: So open border, no sovereignty --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But the incentive -- you say the inventive is -- oh, because they might get healthcare here --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- 10 or 11 million people already here --

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: There's 22 million people here.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- and the second thing is, the real reason that they're leaving is not because of any incentive here, the real reason --

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: No, the front door is open and they get to stay.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: So I guess that's not an incentive?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Hey, listen, Juan seems to think they're on track, so let him.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Thank you.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Donald Trump the centrist now, all right? Look what you did. Fireworks fly as candidates takes aim at Joe Biden, a reaction to the heated exchange between the former V.P. and Kamala Harris, next on “The Five.”

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Democrats focusing on frontrunner Joe Biden at last night faceoff. One of the most intense moments when Kamala Harris blasted the former vice president over his race record and recent comments about working with segregationist senators.

utterances.speaker: SEN. KAMALA HARRIS, D-CALIF.
utterances.utterance: I do not believe you're a racist, and I agree with you when you commit yourself to the importance of finding common ground. But I also believe and it's personal -- and I was actually very -- it was hurtful to hear you talk about the reputation of two United States senators who built their reputations and career on segregation of race in this country. You also worked with them to oppose bussing. And, you know, there was a little girl in California, who was part of the second class to integrate her public school and she was bussed to school every day. And that little girl was me.

utterances.speaker: JOE BIDEN, FORMER VICE PRESIDENT
utterances.utterance: Mischaracterize my position across the board, I did not praise racists, that is not true.

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.utterance: Do you agree today that you were wrong to oppose bussing in America then?

utterances.speaker: BIDEN
utterances.utterance: No.

utterances.speaker: HARRIS
utterances.utterance: Do you agree?

utterances.speaker: BIDEN
utterances.utterance: I did not oppose bussing in America, what I opposed is bussing ordered by the Department of Education, that's what I opposed. Look, everything I have done in my career, I ran because of civil rights, I continue to think we have to make fundamental changes in civil rights.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: So that was a hot topic last night. And then today, Joe Biden went to Chicago, he was at the rainbow coalition and he decided to try to address this issue again. Watch this.

utterances.speaker: BIDEN
utterances.utterance: I want to be absolutely clear about my record and position on racial justice, including bussing. I never, never, never ever opposed voluntary bussing. It's a constitutional question, to protect the civil rights of every single American. And that's always been my position.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Jesse, we've been talking about, leading up to the debate, that Joe Biden is really -- the only one there who has to defend a 45-year record with things that had done -- happened in the past, attitudes that have changed, things are different now, and he looked like the candidate of the past.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And there's more where that came from. They can get them on Anita Hill. They can get them on the --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: High amendment. There's a lot of material there, and it didn't look good. He was fumbling. He was bumbling. He was stumbling. He wouldn't look her in the eye. And we didn't play the end of the soundbite where he just threw in the towel and says, oh, my time's up, didn't even want to fight. And that's the thing about Joe, he doesn't look like he wants this, he clearly does not have the stomach for this fight, he was unprepared. I don't know if he was not briefed or didn't soak up the briefing. But either way, that was not the way you handle it. You say, excuse me, I was the first black president's vice president, you know me better than that, Kamala. How dare you suggest that I'm racist at all. I've fought for these issues my whole life. Obama wouldn't put me on the ticket if he had any doubts about my sincerity on that issue. Please. And then move on. But she landed a huge punch. I don't know if she got knock out power. He has glass jaw. Well, that would still be determined. But Kamala, very aggressive in a prosecutorial sense. But I just don't know if she's likeable or inspiring enough. It looks like now she could get the nomination, but it's still early. But I'm not so sure she could beat Donald Trump. I still doesn't think she has what it takes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Greg, last night he was -- did not have a teleprompter, nobody did, but today when he has his teleprompter he was able to explain himself better. Is that good?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No, she flattened him. What he said at the debate was she mischaracterized him. He didn't praise racist. Well, now you got a taste of your own medicine because he accused Trump of praising racists, when he hadn't. So what happened to Joe, just happened to him. That's why I have no sympathy for him, even though he's a nice guy. And she did mischaracterize him. There's no question he did. But that's too bad because this is the left, it's about interpreting what someone says in its very worst light. So everything always leads back to you're a racist. If you want a strong police force, racist, even if it's minority police force. If you want strong borders, that's racist, even if all people want a strong border. If you want to move homeless in camps, encampments, that's racist, too. But let's not forget, this is the best part about this whole thing, because I think Kamala is moving toward the nomination.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: She jailed a lot of poor people for low-level drug and nonviolent offenses. So her past is as checkered as Joe's, which means, what Joe did to Trump and what Kamala did to Joe is what Liz is going to do to Kamala.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And you know that they suggested that when Joe said, you know, I went into this business as a public defender, you wouldn't do it as a prosecutor.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Right, exactly.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: So I think he's telegraphing that.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: That was interesting. Juan, last night there was a lot of these, sort of live polling situations, and Gabe -- is a reporter and he was in Iowa watching one of these live dial ones, like the Franklin ones they do, and what's interesting -- we're all feeling like Biden got -- it handed to him. Then at this event in Iowa where they have African-American voters that are undecided in the debate -- in the process, they actually -- their dials went up for Kamala Harris, but they also went up in Biden's response. So, perhaps, conventional wisdom, or at least on twitter, might not be representative of how people feel.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I'm glad you reached that conclusion. I reached that one a long time ago. Twitter is not reflective of reality.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: We've said that before. I'm just saying that this was from last night.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Right. I think -- you know, the media loves the idea that you flatten or bury, right, the obituaries for the front-runner, it's a good story. I just don't think it's true. And they also like the phoenix rising in terms of Kamala Harris. I think Kamala Harris had a very good night. I think she was strong. I thought she was persuasive. I thought she -- not only spoke the policy, she personalized it, said, this is me. This is me on the bus. I'm the little black girl that you would not have been on that bus if it was up to you. I do think that Vice President Biden was prepared, Jesse. I think he had that line that you referenced right in his pocket, which was, you know what, I was a public defender after Dr. King was killed in Delaware, I wasn't the prosecutor. So I'm standing with the little guy. I think, though, when you look at this, what you have to understand is, and I said this to you guys yesterday, this is going to be different than Wednesday night. Joe Biden is the front-runner. You know, Elizabeth Warren was the leader among a smaller group of people. But there's no question, if you want to move up in this race, you want to make your mark right now, you've got to go after Joe Biden. They went after Joe Biden. She went after Joe Biden on race. Race was a big -- you know, the thing with Buttigieg was also big. But guess what? Pass the torch. Eric Swalwell said, why don't you pass the torch, old man. He might as well said, you old dog.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: When Eric Swalwell said that, Katie, I felt the room pulling for Joe Biden.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Right, there we go.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Well, the juxtaposition and the split screen between Kamala Harris and Joe Biden really is a view of what the far-left and the base is looking at here. They're trying to say, we need to move on, we don't want Joe Biden. He's part of the problem. He's part of the establishment. We want someone younger who has different ideas. But I found that Democrats are perfectly happy with accusing Republicans of racism when it's convenient, but when it comes to the record of people in their party, they're willing to throw it away like it doesn't matter. Virginia is a good example of that with the governor in either black face or a KKK garb. Joe Biden does have a history of praising segregationists. I know he wants to say he doesn't, but he gave a speech in 1998 for segregationist senator, John Stennis, a Democrat from Mississippi, saying he'd done great during his time in the Senate. He does have a record that Kamala Harris is going to be able to look at, whether that resonates with the country, I'm not sure. I think people are sick of being accused of racism overall, so whether this will land on Joe Biden as a long-term punch, we'll just have to see.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Can I make a prediction? It's a -- I believe it's going to be two women on the ticket.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: OK. One thing before we go --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You don't want to know which one?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Oh, because loser. All right, Mayor Pete feeling the heat -- over the police shooting in his hometown of South Bend. We'll talk about that next on “The Five.”

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Pete Buttigieg in the hot seat at last night's Democratic debate. The South Bend, Indiana, mayor getting grilled about his handling of the deadly shooting of a black man by a white cop in his city. It has outraged residents.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Your community of South Bend, Indiana, has recently been in uproar over an officer-involved shooting. The police force in South Bend is now 6 percent black in a city that is 26 percent black. Why has that not improved over your two terms as mayor?

utterances.speaker: PETE BUTTIGIEG, SOUTH BEND MAYOR
utterances.utterance: Because I couldn't get it done. My community is in anguish right now because of an officer-involved shooting, a black man, Eric Logan, killed by a white officer. I'm not allowed to take sides until the investigation comes back. The officer said he was attacked with a knife, but he didn't have his body camera on. It's a mess and we're hurting.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Mayor Pete's 2020 rivals they're wasting no time hitting him over his response to that incident.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: I think that the question they're asking in South Bend, I think across the country, is why has it taken so long?

utterances.speaker: BUTTIGIEG
utterances.utterance: I've got to respond to that. Look, we've taken so many steps toward police accountability that, you know, the FOP just denounced me for too much accountability. We're obviously not there yet. And I accept responsibility.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: The camera wasn't on and that's a policy, and you should fire the chief.

utterances.speaker: BUTTIGIEG
utterances.utterance: So under Indiana law, this will be investigated and there will be accountability for the officer involved.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: But you're the mayor, you should fire the chief if that's the policy and someone died.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think he glared at him there, Katie. I think he didn't want to fire the chief. But let me just say, I thought the show of humility -- I thought it was appealing that he said, you know, I was wrong. On the other hand, the facts of the -- the reality of the incident don't go away.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Well, you know, I actually give Mayor Pete a lot of credit for taking a step back and not jumping to conclusions about what happened and saying I'm going to let the investigation play out before I take a side, because as we've seen in a number of these incidents, not all of them, but the big ones that the media has run with, Ferguson, Baltimore, all of the calls from the media and politicians in Washington have said, you need to do this, you need to do this and the facts come out and what actually happened is opposite of the story. So I give him a lot of respect for taking a moment, a breather and saying we're going to listen to what the facts say before we make big decisions.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Jesse, the question that emerges is Pete Buttigieg comes off as a little bit of political novice, Mayor of a small city--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Sure.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Has not been through it. And this is a test for him. I don't know if he aced it last night, but the test goes on and it will be a drag going forward.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I think he has momentum. The Kamala, Biden thing overshadowed it. But he performed on Team Pete. He's likeable. He's got a crisp military serious dialect, but he's also likeable because he has this deep voice which calms you down and brings you in. It doesn't sound like it canned gimmicky politician. He had some really smooth answers with Medicare as opposed to having an option for private health care. And a great line about I want to deliver an opportunity where if you're a black or a white driver, you're still going to feel the same way when you get pulled over. But I think Swalwell kind of rocked him, kind of with cheap shots. Swalwell doesn't really know the internal municipal politics of it. But it kind of landed and Mayor Pete just kind of looked at him like you didn't have anything to say.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So Dana what do you think? Do you think he managed it?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I think he was refreshing and I'm not - I'm not - he can take all the blame on himself, but he's - he'll wait. But he said I didn't get the job done. He didn't try to spin it. I do think that's authenticity - authenticity that we all have been talking about. But I also noticed something else about him, and I agree with Jesse. He's very polished when he speaks. But one of the things is that he also commands respect from other people in the room. So while others words tripping over themselves, crosstalk trying to interrupt, trying to - when he was called on or when he meant to speak everyone else stopped talking and listened to him. So he has something when it comes so a leadership quality and ability to hold the room's attention.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Greg, one last point on this is that he doesn't have much support in black America and it looks like it doesn't have much support in black South Bend. So what does that mean going forward given this moment?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I don't know. And I don't know if that has - I would believe that has almost nothing to do with this incident. Because 95 percent of the population doesn't even know what we're talking about, when we're talking about what happened in South Bend. So I doubt when you're doing the polling of blacks, which I haven't seen so I don't know, it has nothing to do with this incident. Because I still don't know much about it and most people don't know. I agree with you, though, that he's - he commands respect. It's hard to credit somebody though for taking the only option, which is the only option he add which is saying whoops. But it shows one thing about the Biden thing which we said before. This race - the racial smear is not a generational thing. OK? It's hitten Biden now. It's hitting Mayor Pete. But now it's because every issue is infused with Vitamin R - "Vitamin Race". It's - a lot of it is media generated - not all of it. But a lot of it is, because division sells. So this is just a reality. It's got to tear the country apart. Maybe that's what the media wants.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, we don't want that. Coming up, the strangest moments from last night's debate to entertain you. Stay with us on “The Five.”

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Well, there was no shortage of cringe worthy moments from last night's debate. First up Jesse and Greg predicted, Eric Swalwell would pull a stunt and boy did he deliver.

utterances.speaker: REP. ERIC SWALWELL, D-CALIF., PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: I'm a Congressman, but also a father of a 2-year-old, an infant. And I'm not changing diapers, I'm changing Washington. Most the time to diaper smelled better--

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Not many times you practice that in the mirror. Next, new age self-help guru Marianne Williamson gave us an insight to her unique strategies.

utterances.speaker: MARIANNE WILLIAMSON, D-PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: My first call is to Prime Minister of New Zealand, who said that her goal is to make New Zealand a place where it's the best place in the world for a child to grow up. I would tell her, "Girlfriend, you are so wrong", because the United States of America is going to be the best place in the world for a child to grow up. Mr. President, if you're listening, I want you to hear me please. You have harnessed fear for political purposes and only love can cast that out. So, I Sir, I have a feeling you know what you're doing. I'm going to harness love for political purposes. I will meet you on that field and Sir love will win.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: The field of love. And Kirsten Gillibrand and the other candidates get shut down in epic fashion after constantly interrupting each other.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: In Bernie's bill, in Bernie's bill I wrote--

utterances.speaker: SAVANNAH GUTHRIE, ANCHOR, NBC NEWS
utterances.utterance: Senator, we are going to talk about healthcare at length Senator, but at the moment my colleague would say--

utterances.speaker: SEN. KIRSTEN GILLIBRAND, D-N.Y., PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: In Senator Sanders' bill I wrote the part in Senator Sanders' bill--

utterances.speaker: SEN. BERNIE SANDERS, I-VT, D-PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: As part of Joe's generation-

utterances.speaker: PETE BUTTIGIEG, D-PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: I'm all for--

utterances.speaker: GILLIBRAND
utterances.utterance: Before we move on-

utterances.speaker: SANDERS
utterances.utterance: As part of Joe's generation - let me respond.

utterances.speaker: GILLIBRAND
utterances.utterance: Before - before we move-

utterances.speaker: SANDERS
utterances.utterance: The issue, if I may say--

utterances.speaker: GILLIBRAND
utterances.utterance: Before we move on from education--

utterances.speaker: SANDERS
utterances.utterance: That is not generational--

utterances.speaker: JOSE DIAZ-BALART, ANCHOR, NBC NEWS
utterances.utterance: Yes, please, please. Senators--

utterances.speaker: SEN. KAMALA HARRIS, D-CALIF., PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: Hey, guys. You know what? America does not want to witness a food fight. They want to know how we're going to put food on their table.

utterances.speaker: LESTER HOLT, ANCHOR, NBC NEWS
utterances.utterance: Kirsten Gillibrand - Senator Gillibrand.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Can I--

utterances.speaker: GILLIBRAND
utterances.utterance: Yes. So, now, it's my turn.

utterances.speaker: HOLT
utterances.utterance: Go ahead.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Food on your table on a field of love, Greg.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I've got to tell you something man. Marianne Williamson has something that makes you just want to listen to her - curl up and listen to her. You know what that's what she's talking. It's like a made for TV Hallmark movie in which two people are running for president and she says, "I'm going to beat you in the field of love". You bet. And then they end up falling in love and they end up becoming Co- Presidents, because she's like straight out of Falcon Crest. Like in mid- 80s. She's like an older Charlie's Angel. And she just walked right into my heart and stole it.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Jesse? Return to love?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I'm developing feelings for Williamson also. I have to confess. There's something enchanting about her, the way she talks, the way her elocution just draws you in. I'm mesmerized--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Me too.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I'm fascinated. I want to get to know her. I want to go out for drinks with her maybe two or three. Would you please come on Watters World? We'd love to have you. Swalwell, we predicted, he is a corndog, it's always got. Gillibrand as much, as I like Williamson, I'm beginning to loath Gillibrand. The constant interrupting and the whining when she has nothing to say is driving me crazy and I just need to calm down.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: So Dana, all of these jokes - the corny jokes are trying to send a message - right. Trying to break through, maybe try to be authentic, I'm a cool guy so I can say some things that are not so political. But do some of these things come off as trying too hard?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Oh, yes, Eric Swalwell for sure. And the - I have to feel like the Governor Hickenlooper was sitting there a little bit out of place, just like wait, I I've done things actually. And then I think Michael Bennet had a pretty decent debate, the Senator from Colorado. But let's go back to this that Bernie Sanders after pulling the party so far to the Left that now it feels, like to a David Brooks, that they are unelectable, is basically fading completely from the conversation--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's ironic.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Nobody even wanted to take him on. No one bothered to take him on. It was really interesting.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Juan. I thought that Elizabeth Warren kind of leapfrogged him the night before. And take the--

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes, she have been leapfrogging her, so I think that these two nights really seal that that it's her moment and she's got that lane in terms of Left wing Democratic Party politics. At least she's rising and he's fading. We'll see what happens. I will say this. I think the field is just too big, so you get some people who really shouldn't be on the stage.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Like who?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Don't say Marianne, Juan?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes. Because you know what, I am going to use this as my evidence. Here's my evidence, right. The fact that Greg and Jesse are lover lover, I'm just crazy about--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: We are crossing the aisle.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, no. You guys see her as like - by the way, USA one today in soccer. You see her as a ball to kick around and make fun of Democrats.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes, yes, yes, let me just say.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I find Jesse and Greg not just open minded, but open hearted.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Exactly.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I like her.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Any time that they can mock at Democrat they're--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: We are not mocking her. I'm legitimately interested in her.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes, you should be more concerned that they're sincere.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Why you are worried about love? You don't like love?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: The laggards who got mocked became President of United States.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes. Well, and the mockery continues. But I would say that I think that when you look at someone like Swalwell, I just thought he looks stiff. You look like that - you know what's that guy in the Wizard of Oz, the guy of the--

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Tin Can.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes, he just looked like he was stuck there. And--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Why are you mocking him Juan?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I'm not mocking him.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You are mocking him, you just called him a robot.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, I don't know. But I really think that Yang and Bernie are in a way the reverse stories here, because I thought Yang was going to pop. I'm amazed at what happened to Bernie. So--

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: All right. Well--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Bernie--

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Don't go anywhere. "Fan Mail Friday" is up next.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: "Fan Mail Friday", let's get started. From Tracy, "What was your worst job interview?" Jesse?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: My worst job interview was I interviewed with Anderson Cooper actually--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That's pretty good.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And he's - I didn't know he was on the show "The Mole". So I was like, "Oh, that was you?"

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Nice.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And that ended bad.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That was bad. That's bad. You insulted him.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes, insulted him.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Katie?

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: I don't know if I've had a really bad job interview, to be honest. I nailed my first interview.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I nailed it.
